90":"1433–1490","1435–1481":"1435–1481","1438–1480":"1438–1480","1440–1527":"1440–1527","1440":"1440","1481":"1481","1480":"1480","1490":"1490","1404":"1404","1447":"1447","1435":"1435","1479":"1479","1433":"1433","1400":"1400","about 1438":"about 1438","about 1435":"about 1435","1442":"1442","1430":"1430","about 1433":"about 1433","about 1430":"about 1430","1428":"1428","1527":"1527","1438":"1438","East Dereham, Breckland, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom":"Dereham, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom","East Dereham, Norfolk, England":"Dereham, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Hayfield","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English: locative name from Hayfield (Derbys)."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]},{"name":"Elizabeth","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["The usual spelling of   Elisabeth   in English. It is recorded in the medieval period, but was made popular by being borne by  Queen Elizabeth I  of England (  1533–1603 ). In the 20th century it again became extremely fashionable, partly because it was the name of  Elizabeth Bowes-Lyon  (  1900–2002 ), who in  1936  became Queen Elizabeth as the wife of King George VI, and after his death in  1952  achieved great public affection as Queen Mother for nearly half a century. Even more influentially, it is the name of her daughter  Queen Elizabeth II  (  b. 1926 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Elisabeth","meanings":["The spelling of   Elizabeth   used in the Authorized Version of the New Testament, and in most modern European languages. This was the name of the mother of John the Baptist (Luke 1:60). Etymologically, the name means ‘God is my oath’, and is therefore identical with <i>Elisheba</i>, the name of the wife of Aaron according to the genealogy at Exodus 6:23. The final element seems to have been altered by association with Hebrew <i>shabbāth</i> ‘Sabbath’."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Margaret Elizabeth Hayfield was born in 1404, in Dereham, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom. She married William Flegg in 1428. They were the parents of at least 3 sons and 2 daughters. She died in 1442, in her hometown, at the age of 38."},"et":{"1404–1442":"1404–1442","1400–1447":"1400–1447","1430–1479":"1430–1479","1433–1490":"1433–1490","1435–1481":"1435–1481","1438–1480":"1438–1480","1440–1527":"1440–1527","1440":"1440","1481":"1481","1480":"1480","1490":"1490","1404":"1404","1447":"1447","1435":"1435","1479":"1479","1433":"1433","1400":"1400","about 1438":"umbes 1438","about 1435":"umbes 1435","1442":"1442","1430":"1430","about 1433":"umbes 1433","about 1430":"umbes 1430","1428":"1428","1527":"1527","1438":"1438","East Dereham, Breckland, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom":"Dereham, Norfolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","East Dereham, Norfolk, England":"Dereham, Norfolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1404–1442":"1404–1442","1400–1447":"1400–1447","1430–1479":"1430–1479","1433–1490":"1433–1490","1435–1481":"1435–1481","1438–1480":"1438–1480","1440–1527":"1440–1527","1440":"1440","1481":"1481","1480":"1480","1490":"1490","1404":"1404","1447":"1447","1435":"1435","1479":"1479","1433":"1433","1400":"1400","about 1438":"noin 1438","about 1435":"noin 1435","1442":"1442","1430":"1430","about 1433":"noin 1433","about 1430":"noin 1430","1428":"1428","1527":"1527","1438":"1438","East Dereham, Breckland, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom":"Dereham, Norfolk, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","East Dereham, Norfolk, England":"Dereham, Norfolk, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1404–1442":"1404–1442",